    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Arnica montana improperly include developing skin irritation, such as redness, itching, and rashes, due to its high concentration of sesquiterpene lactones that can cause phototoxicity when exposed to sunlight. Arnica montana may also interact with certain medications, like blood thinners, diabetes medications, and immunosuppressants, by increasing the risk of bleeding, hypoglycemia, or worsening of underlying conditions. Excessive use of Arnica montana can exacerbate inflammation, particularly in individuals with pre-existing conditions like eczema, psoriasis, or rosacea. Some people may experience allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, hives, and swelling, especially if they are sensitive to members of the Asteraceae family. Furthermore, improper use of Arnica montana can lead to the worsening of underlying health conditions, such as liver or kidney problems, due to its potential liver toxicity and interactions with other substances."
